      "prompt": "How do I run a lean experiment?",
      "response": "Quick answer: a lean experiment is one trip around the Build-Measure-Learn loop with a pre-declared decision rule. Six steps, but the discipline is in steps 1 and 3, not the build itself.

The 6 Steps
#	Step	The question it answers	The trap if you skip it
1	State the hypothesis as a falsifiable claim	"We believe X; if true, doing Y will produce Z"	"Users will love it" — unfalsifiable, can't lose, can't learn
2	Design the experiment — the smallest activity that exposes the hypothesis to real signal	"What's the cheapest probe that real users would touch?"	Building a feature when a landing page would've answered it
3	Declare metrics + thresholds before the run	"What number, observed on what cohort, counts as conclusive?"	Post-hoc rationalization — "well, 3 signups kind of validates it…"
4	Run it — build the smallest probe, expose to real users, instrument	"Did we expose the hypothesis to truth?"	Internal-only run = dogfooding, not validation
5	Analyze against the pre-declared thresholds	"Did the data clear the bar we set, yes or no?"	Moving the goalposts mid-analysis
6	Pivot-or-persevere decision, reasoning recorded	"What changes Monday morning because of what we learned?"	"Interesting data" with no decision = theater
Two non-negotiables
Falsifiable hypothesis. If you can't describe the result that would make you abandon the idea, you don't have a hypothesis — you have a wish. The experiment exists to change someone's mind. If the result is predictable in advance, don't run it.

Pre-declared decision rule. Before you launch, write down: "If we see ≥ X by Y date with cohort Z, we persevere. Below X, we pivot. Between X and threshold Y, we run a refinement." Lock this in before you have data — humans are excellent at retrofitting interpretations to outcomes they like.

Concrete shape — borrowing your AI email summarizer example
Step	Filled in
Hypothesis	"We believe ≥30% of executives in mid-market SaaS will grant inbox access to a third-party AI summarizer; if true, [N=20] cohort outreach will produce ≥6 access grants within 14 days."
Experiment	Concierge MVP — manual summaries via founder + a Calendly link. No build.
Metrics + thresholds	Grant rate ≥30% = persevere; <15% = pivot to in-platform alternative; 15–30% = run refinement on segmentation
Run	2 weeks, founder personally outreaches 20 execs from warm network
Analyze	Count grants. Note objections verbatim.
Decide	Above threshold → MVP build. Below → pivot the access model entirely.
That experiment costs you 2 weeks of founder time and answers Assumption C from the MVP discussion. No code.

Two ways to proceed:

You want to run one for real? Bring me the hypothesis (or the half-baked version of it) and we'll run LE end-to-end. I'll refuse to advance if step 1 isn't falsifiable, fair warning.
You want to understand the discipline more deeply? Stay in chat mode and ask. I'll happily walk through pivot-vs-persevere reasoning, instrumentation patterns, common failure modes — whatever's useful.
