Three questions that decide whether this is actually a win:

What was the hypothesis the feature was testing? If you can't answer this in one sentence, the feature wasn't an experiment, it was a wish — and "shipping a wish on time" is just expensive theater. (If it was an experiment, what counts as evidence it worked? Were thresholds declared before ship?)

Are real users using it? Not "the feature works" — adoption. Activation rate among the target cohort, retention past day 7, the share of intended users who touch it more than once. Shipping ≠ usage. Most shipped features die quietly in the analytics.

Did the metric you actually cared about move? Whatever business or user outcome justified the build — has it shifted in the predicted direction? If you didn't define the outcome metric before shipping, you can't answer this, which is itself a finding.

