      "response": "Now we're talking. "Before we build" is exactly the right instinct — most teams ship priority-support tiers and then wonder why nobody upgrades. You're asking the right question at the right time.

Here's how I'd think about it.

The central trap: stated ≠ revealed preference
If you ask SMB customers "would you pay $20/month for priority support?" — a meaningful percentage will say yes. Most of them will not actually pay. Surveys overestimate willingness-to-pay by 2–5x consistently across categories. Any experiment that ends in "they said they'd pay" rather than "they paid (or hit the buy button)" is weak signal at best.

So the design principle: make the customer take a real action that costs them something — money, time, attention, or commitment. The closer to a credit card, the better.

The ladder of experiments — from cheap-and-weak to expensive-and-strong
Signal Strength	Experiment	What it costs you	What you actually learn
⚡ Weak	Pricing survey / interview	A week of outreach	What people say they'd pay. Useful for ruling out "$20 is way too high" but not for "$20 works."
⚡⚡ Medium	Pricing page experiment — add a "Priority Support — $20/mo" tier to your existing pricing page; measure clicks on it	A page edit, 2-week A/B	Click-through is interest signal. No commitment, but better than asking.
⚡⚡⚡ Strong	Fake door / Painted door — pricing page tier, click "Upgrade" → a real-looking checkout flow → at the credit-card step, "We're rolling this out gradually — want early access?" Capture email + the fact they were willing to pay	2–4 days of dev for the painted door, 2-week run	They hit Buy. That's revealed intent, even without the charge clearing.
⚡⚡⚡⚡ Strongest	Concierge tier — pick 10–20 customers from your target SMB segment, offer "priority support" manually delivered (founder/CSM responds within 2hr, escalation channel, whatever you'd promise) for $20/mo for 60 days. Real charge, real service, zero product build.	2 months of someone's calendar, modest revenue offset	Actual paid conversion + retention + the real complaints/asks. This is the gold standard for SaaS WTP.
⚡⚡⚡⚡⚡ Pre-sell	Pre-sell with charge-on-launch — "Priority Support tier is launching in 30 days. Lock in your spot for $20/mo, charged when service begins. Cancel anytime."	Stripe setup, light copy work	Hardest commitment without delivery. Highest fidelity — but only run this if you actually intend to ship if the result is positive.
My recommendation
Run #4 (Concierge) — possibly preceded by #3 (Painted door) if you need a top-of-funnel signal first.

Concierge is the one I'd put money on for SMB priority support specifically, for three reasons:

You learn what "priority support" actually means to SMBs. Is it 2-hour response? Phone access? A dedicated rep? Faster bug-fix turnaround? You don't know yet, and surveys won't tell you. Manually delivering the tier teaches you the real job-to-be-done before you build a single feature.
Real money clears. $20/mo on a credit card is not a vanity metric — it's the metric.
Retention is the kicker. A WTP test only tells you they'll try it. The 60-day window catches the "paid in month one, churned in month two" pattern that kills priority-tier economics.
Painted door (#3) is a useful precursor only if you don't have 10–20 willing pilot customers in your warm network. If you do, skip to concierge — painted door tells you click-rate, concierge tells you the actual answer.

What we need to declare before running — non-negotiable
This is the part teams skip and then regret. Before the first cohort message goes out, write down:

Decision input	Pre-declared
Target cohort	"SMB" is too broad. 10–50 employees? Specific verticals? Customers above $X MRR or below? Pin this.
Sample size	15–20 outreach for concierge. Bigger if your warm network supports it.
Conversion threshold for "persevere"	What % paid conversion = build? My priors: ≥25% pay-and-retain at 60 days = strong signal to build. 10–25% = pivot the offer (price, scope, segment). <10% = priority support is not the wedge.
Retention threshold	What % stay paying past day 60? Below ~70% retention even at good conversion means the tier doesn't deliver perceived value — pricing isn't the issue, the offer is.
Qualitative signal	Top 3 things customers asked for during the 60 days — these tell you the real feature scope before you build.
If you can't get aligned on those numbers before launching, you'll get into the post-experiment debate of "well, 4 out of 15 isn't terrible..." and lose the learning.

What I'd refuse to do
Pure survey. Survey-only WTP for a $20 priority tier is a coin flip. If a stakeholder is pushing for it, run it as a cheap precursor to concierge, not as the validation itself.
Build a "lite" version of the feature first. This is the trap the question is dodging — and rightly. No build until paid conversion clears the bar.
Want me to design the concierge experiment end-to-end? Bring me your customer segment definition (or "we don't have one yet" — also a finding) and we'll run it through LE with hypothesis, thresholds, and decision rule locked in before week one."
